const QUESTIONS_CCSP_C6 = [
  { id:2001, domain:1, level:3, question:"A SaaS provider hosts a multi-tenant application on IaaS rented from a public cloud. When mapping shared responsibility, who is accountable to the SaaS customer for securing the underlying hypervisor?", options:["A jointly appointed third-party auditor who validates the hypervisor configuration","The IaaS cloud provider, since they physically own and operate the virtualization layer","The SaaS customer, because they consume the application and accept residual risk","The SaaS provider, because the customer contracts only with them and inherits the IaaS controls"], correct:3, explanation:"The SaaS provider is contractually accountable to its customers for the full stack it offers, even where it inherits hypervisor controls from the IaaS provider. The IaaS provider operates the hypervisor but has no contractual relationship with the SaaS customer." },
  { id:2002, domain:1, level:3, question:"An architect must choose a deployment model for a regulated workload that needs elasticity but also strict tenant isolation and dedicated hardware for a defined period. Which model BEST balances these needs?", options:["Private cloud using dedicated infrastructure with elastic internal provisioning","Community cloud shared among organizations with similar compliance needs","Hybrid cloud bursting sensitive data into public capacity on demand","Public cloud with logical multi-tenant isolation enforced by the provider"], correct:0, explanation:"A private cloud on dedicated hardware delivers strict isolation and elasticity within owned capacity, satisfying both requirements. Public multi-tenant isolation is logical only and does not meet the dedicated-hardware constraint." },
  { id:2003, domain:1, level:3, question:"During design review, the team debates where to terminate TLS for an internet-facing API. Which consideration MOST strongly favors terminating at the load balancer rather than the application server?", options:["It removes the need to encrypt traffic on the internal network segment","It guarantees end-to-end confidentiality from client to application logic","It allows centralized certificate management and offloads cryptographic processing","It satisfies all data-in-transit regulatory requirements by default"], correct:2, explanation:"Terminating at the load balancer centralizes certificate lifecycle and offloads crypto, the strongest design rationale. It does not provide end-to-end confidentiality, since the internal hop must be separately protected." },
  { id:2004, domain:1, level:3, question:"A CSP offers a managed KMS where it controls the hardware security modules. A customer with strict sovereignty rules wants to retain ultimate control of key material. Which approach BEST meets the requirement?", options:["Use provider-managed keys with envelope encryption and rotation enabled","Adopt hold-your-own-key so keys never leave customer-controlled HSMs","Adopt bring-your-own-key, importing keys into the provider HSM","Disable encryption at rest and rely on physical datacenter controls"], correct:1, explanation:"Hold-your-own-key keeps key material in customer-controlled HSMs, giving ultimate control needed for sovereignty. BYOK still imports keys into the provider's HSM, so the provider retains custody of the material." },
  { id:2005, domain:1, level:3, question:"When designing BCDR for a cloud-native application, the team sets an RTO of 15 minutes and an RPO near zero. Which architecture is the MOST appropriate starting point?", options:["Active-active multi-region with synchronous data replication","Pilot light with core services scaled down in a secondary region","Warm standby with reduced-capacity replicas in another region","Backup and restore from object storage in a single region nightly"], correct:0, explanation:"An RPO near zero with a 15-minute RTO requires active-active multi-region and synchronous replication so no committed data is lost. Warm standby introduces failover delay and asynchronous lag that would breach the near-zero RPO." },
  { id:2006, domain:1, level:3, question:"An organization wants to reduce capital expenditure and shift to operational expenditure while retaining the ability to customize the operating system. Which service model FIRST satisfies this?", options:["Software as a Service with vendor-managed application stack","Platform as a Service with managed runtimes and middleware","Infrastructure as a Service with customer-managed operating systems","Function as a Service with event-driven ephemeral execution"], correct:2, explanation:"IaaS shifts capex to opex while letting the customer fully customize the operating system. PaaS abstracts the OS away, so it cannot satisfy the OS-customization requirement." },
  { id:2007, domain:1, level:3, question:"A trusted cloud design references a hardware root of trust. What is the PRIMARY security benefit it provides during system startup?", options:["It encrypts all tenant data automatically before it reaches storage","It isolates tenant workloads by enforcing network micro-segmentation","It establishes a measured boot chain to attest platform integrity","It rotates cryptographic keys on a fixed schedule across the fleet"], correct:2, explanation:"A hardware root of trust anchors a measured boot chain so platform integrity can be attested before workloads run. It does not itself encrypt tenant data or perform network segmentation." },
  { id:2008, domain:1, level:3, question:"An architect evaluates a cloud reference architecture and must decide where to place tenant-specific cryptographic boundaries. Which principle BEST guides the placement decision?", options:["Default to the provider's shared keys to simplify operational overhead","Encrypt only data leaving the cloud to minimize performance impact","Align crypto boundaries with the tenant trust and data classification model","Centralize all keys with the network team for unified visibility"], correct:2, explanation:"Cryptographic boundaries should align with tenant trust zones and data classification so protection matches sensitivity. Defaulting to shared provider keys ignores classification-driven isolation needs." },
  { id:2009, domain:1, level:3, question:"A team is choosing between scaling vertically and horizontally for a stateless web tier expecting unpredictable bursts. Which factor MOST favors horizontal scaling?", options:["It enables elastic capacity and resilience by adding identical instances","It maximizes single-instance CPU and memory before adding nodes","It eliminates the need for a load balancer in front of the tier","It guarantees lower per-request latency than any vertical option"], correct:0, explanation:"Horizontal scaling adds identical stateless instances, delivering elasticity and resilience for unpredictable bursts. Vertical scaling maxes out one instance and offers no fault tolerance if that instance fails." },
  { id:2010, domain:1, level:3, question:"During a design assessment, an architect notes that the CSP's API gateway logs are retained only seven days. For a workload needing one-year audit retention, what is the BEST design response?", options:["Accept the provider default since the gateway is provider-managed","Request the provider extend retention as a contractual exception","Disable gateway logging and rely on application-level logs only","Export gateway logs continuously to customer-controlled long-term storage"], correct:3, explanation:"Exporting logs to customer-controlled storage gives durable, independently retained audit evidence that meets the one-year need. Relying on a provider exception leaves control and durability outside the customer's hands." },
  { id:2011, domain:1, level:3, question:"A cost-benefit analysis compares reserved capacity against on-demand for a steady baseline workload with occasional spikes. Which strategy is MOST cost-effective?", options:["Purchase reserved capacity for the entire peak demand profile","Reserve the steady baseline and use on-demand for the spikes","Use on-demand exclusively to avoid any commitment risk","Move the whole workload to spot capacity to minimize unit price"], correct:1, explanation:"Reserving the predictable baseline captures discount savings while on-demand covers variable spikes cost-effectively. Reserving the full peak wastes spend on capacity that is idle most of the time." },
  { id:2012, domain:1, level:3, question:"An architect must ensure that a compromised tenant cannot affect other tenants' confidentiality in a multi-tenant PaaS. Which control is MOST foundational to that assurance?", options:["Strong logical isolation enforced consistently across the shared platform","Encrypting backups stored in the provider's object storage tier","Periodic penetration testing of the tenant-facing application","A contractual clause assigning liability for any tenant breach"], correct:0, explanation:"Logical isolation is the foundational control preventing one tenant from reaching another's data on shared infrastructure. Penetration testing validates controls but does not by itself create the isolation boundary." },
  { id:2013, domain:1, level:3, question:"When defining functional security requirements for a new cloud service, the team disagrees on portability. Which design choice BEST preserves the ability to migrate between providers later?", options:["Adopt provider-proprietary managed services for fastest delivery","Build on open standards and container abstractions where feasible","Hard-code provider-specific endpoints throughout the application","Store all configuration only in the provider's native secret store"], correct:1, explanation:"Using open standards and container abstractions reduces lock-in and preserves portability across providers. Heavy reliance on proprietary managed services and hard-coded endpoints increases switching costs." },
  { id:2014, domain:1, level:3, question:"A reference architecture mandates defense in depth for an internet-facing tier. Which combination BEST embodies that principle rather than redundant overlap?", options:["WAF, network segmentation, host hardening, and input validation","Two web application firewalls from the same vendor in series","Three identical TLS terminations chained at different hops","Multiple copies of the same intrusion signature set on one device"], correct:0, explanation:"Layering distinct controls at different levels (network, host, application) is true defense in depth. Stacking duplicate identical controls adds redundancy at one layer but not diverse, complementary protection." },
  { id:2015, domain:1, level:3, question:"An organization adopting cloud must decide how to handle a workload subject to data residency rules. Which design decision MOST directly addresses residency?", options:["Encrypt the data with customer-managed keys before uploading it to the provider","Enable versioning on the storage bucket for recovery purposes","Apply role-based access control to limit who can read the data","Select provider regions and availability zones within the required jurisdiction"], correct:3, explanation:"Choosing provider regions inside the required jurisdiction directly satisfies data residency constraints. Encryption protects confidentiality but does not control the physical location where data is stored." },
  { id:2016, domain:1, level:3, question:"During design, a stakeholder proposes relying solely on the CSP's certifications to demonstrate compliance for a customer-built application. Why is this reasoning flawed?", options:["Provider certifications cover only the customer-managed configuration layer","Provider certifications never apply to any part of the shared model","Certifications expire monthly and cannot be relied upon for design","Certifications cover provider responsibilities, not customer-built layers"], correct:3, explanation:"Provider certifications attest to provider-managed responsibilities, but the customer must independently demonstrate compliance for layers it controls. Inheriting provider attestations does not cover the customer-built application." },
  { id:2017, domain:1, level:3, question:"An architect is selecting a cryptographic approach for data shared with an external partner who must decrypt it. Which design is MOST appropriate?", options:["Symmetric encryption with the key embedded in the shared file","Asymmetric encryption using the partner's public key for confidentiality","Hashing the data so the partner can verify but not read it","Tokenization with the token vault held only by the sender"], correct:1, explanation:"Asymmetric encryption with the partner's public key lets only the partner decrypt using their private key, ideal for sharing. Embedding a symmetric key in the file exposes it to anyone who obtains the file." },
  { id:2018, domain:2, level:3, question:"A data team must protect a production analytics dataset so developers can run realistic queries without exposing real PII. Which technique BEST meets this need while preserving referential integrity?", options:["Format-preserving tokenization consistent across related fields","Dynamic data masking applied only at query display time","Full-disk encryption of the analytics storage volumes","Irreversible hashing of every PII column in the dataset"], correct:0, explanation:"Format-preserving, consistent tokenization keeps referential integrity across joined fields while removing real PII. Irreversible hashing breaks the ability to join related records and degrades analytic usefulness." },
  { id:2019, domain:2, level:3, question:"In the cloud data lifecycle, an organization wants to enforce that data classification drives controls automatically as data is created. Which phase is the MOST effective point to apply classification?", options:["The Store phase, after data has settled into its repository","The Create phase, tagging data as it is generated or ingested","The Use phase, when an application first reads the data","The Destroy phase, to decide retention before deletion"], correct:1, explanation:"Classifying at the Create phase lets controls follow the data through every later phase. Waiting until Store means data may already have been handled without appropriate protection." },
  { id:2020, domain:2, level:3, question:"A company must demonstrate that deleted customer data in a public cloud is truly unrecoverable. Given that physical media is provider-controlled, which approach is MOST reliable?", options:["Request the provider physically degauss the underlying drives","Crypto-shred by destroying the keys protecting the encrypted data","Overwrite the logical volumes with multiple random passes","Delete the storage bucket and trust provider garbage collection"], correct:1, explanation:"Crypto-shredding destroys the keys, rendering encrypted data unrecoverable without needing physical media access the customer cannot get. Physical degaussing is impractical because the customer does not control the shared media." },
  { id:2021, domain:2, level:3, question:"An IRM solution is proposed to protect sensitive documents that leave the corporate boundary. Which capability MOST distinguishes IRM from standard file encryption?", options:["It enforces usage policies like print and copy restrictions after access","It encrypts the file at rest using a strong symmetric cipher","It compresses the document to reduce transmission bandwidth","It stores the file in an immutable write-once storage tier"], correct:0, explanation:"IRM enforces persistent usage policies (print, copy, forward, expiry) that travel with the document, unlike plain encryption. Standard encryption only protects confidentiality at rest or in transit, not post-access usage." },
  { id:2022, domain:2, level:3, question:"A security team wants to detect when sensitive data is being copied to unsanctioned cloud storage by employees. Which control is MOST directly suited to this objective?", options:["Data loss prevention monitoring egress for sensitive content","Field-level tokenization within the database of record","Immutable backups retained in a separate region","Multi-factor authentication on the corporate VPN"], correct:0, explanation:"DLP inspects content in motion and can detect or block sensitive data heading to unsanctioned storage. Tokenization protects stored fields but does nothing to detect exfiltration to external services." },
  { id:2023, domain:2, level:3, question:"During data discovery, an analyst finds unstructured documents that may contain regulated data scattered across object storage. Which discovery method is MOST effective for this case?", options:["Label-based discovery relying on existing metadata tags","Network flow analysis of storage access requests","Schema inspection of relational table definitions","Content analysis scanning files for patterns and keywords"], correct:3, explanation:"Content analysis inspects the actual file contents, which is essential for unstructured data lacking reliable tags. Label-based discovery fails when files were never tagged, which is common for ad hoc documents." },
  { id:2024, domain:2, level:3, question:"A regulated firm uses BYOK with a public CSP. Auditors ask how the firm limits the provider's ability to access plaintext. Which BYOK practice MOST strengthens that position?", options:["Allow the provider to cache decrypted keys for performance","Share the key with multiple provider regions for availability","Enable external key store so key operations require customer approval","Store the master key alongside the encrypted data for convenience"], correct:2, explanation:"An external key store keeps the key under customer control and requires customer-side authorization for crypto operations, limiting provider plaintext access. Letting the provider cache decrypted keys undermines the very control being claimed." },
  { id:2025, domain:2, level:3, question:"An organization must preserve the chain of custody for cloud-stored evidence during litigation. Which practice is MOST critical to defensibility?", options:["Encrypting the evidence with the strongest available cipher","Granting broad read access so investigators can collaborate freely","Storing the evidence in the cheapest archival tier available","Documenting every handler, timestamp, and integrity hash continuously"], correct:3, explanation:"Continuous documentation of handlers, timestamps, and integrity hashes is the essence of a defensible chain of custody. Strong encryption protects confidentiality but does not establish who handled the evidence and when." },
  { id:2026, domain:2, level:3, question:"A storage architect must choose between object and block storage for a write-once compliance archive needing immutability. Which choice and feature BEST fit?", options:["Block storage with periodic snapshots for point-in-time recovery","File storage with standard POSIX permissions on the archive","Ephemeral instance storage for fast sequential writes","Object storage with write-once-read-many lock policies enabled"], correct:3, explanation:"Object storage with WORM/object-lock enforces immutability required for compliance archives. Block snapshots can be deleted or overwritten and do not provide tamper-proof retention guarantees." },
  { id:2027, domain:2, level:3, question:"A team enables encryption at rest but auditors flag that the CSP holds the keys. For data with the highest sensitivity, what is the BEST improvement?", options:["Migrate to customer-managed keys with strict access logging","Increase the key length from 128-bit to 256-bit symmetric","Rotate the provider-managed keys more frequently each quarter","Add server-side compression before the data is encrypted"], correct:0, explanation:"Customer-managed keys move custody and access control to the customer, directly addressing the provider-holds-keys concern. Increasing key length or rotation frequency does not change who controls the keys." },
  { id:2028, domain:2, level:3, question:"An organization wants to ensure logs of data access events are tamper-evident for forensic use. Which approach MOST directly achieves this?", options:["Forwarding logs to a write-once store with cryptographic hashing","Compressing logs nightly to save storage costs","Restricting log read access to the security team only","Sampling one in ten access events to reduce log volume"], correct:0, explanation:"Write-once storage combined with cryptographic hashing makes any tampering detectable, which is essential for forensic reliability. Restricting read access improves confidentiality but does not make records tamper-evident." },
  { id:2029, domain:2, level:3, question:"During the Archive phase, a company must keep records seven years but rarely access them. Which decision BEST balances cost, retrievability, and compliance?", options:["Keep records in hot storage to guarantee instant retrieval","Delete all records after one year purely to minimize ongoing storage spend","Use cold archival tier with documented retrieval SLAs and retention lock","Replicate records across three hot regions for durability"], correct:2, explanation:"A cold archival tier with retention lock meets the seven-year mandate cost-effectively while documented SLAs ensure acceptable retrieval. Hot storage satisfies compliance but wastes money on rarely accessed data." },
  { id:2030, domain:2, level:3, question:"A developer proposes masking PII by truncating values in application logs. Why might a reviewer consider this insufficient for compliance?", options:["Truncation increases log storage requirements significantly","Truncation violates the data minimization principle entirely","Masking should always be reversible for troubleshooting","Partial values may still allow re-identification when combined"], correct:3, explanation:"Truncated values can be re-identified when correlated with other data, so the masking may not adequately protect PII. The concern is residual re-identification risk, not storage size or reversibility." },
  { id:2031, domain:2, level:3, question:"An analytics platform needs to share datasets with partners while preventing reverse engineering of individuals. Which technique offers the STRONGEST privacy guarantee for aggregate queries?", options:["Differential privacy adding calibrated noise to query results","Static data masking of selected identifier columns","Encrypting the dataset with a shared symmetric key","Row-level filtering based on partner role assignments"], correct:0, explanation:"Differential privacy adds calibrated noise that mathematically bounds re-identification risk for aggregate queries. Masking and filtering reduce exposure but do not provide a formal privacy guarantee against inference." },
  { id:2032, domain:2, level:3, question:"A bucket policy allows public read to support a static website, but it also stores user upload metadata. What is the BEST corrective design?", options:["Enable versioning so deleted public objects can be restored","Separate public web assets and private metadata into distinct buckets","Encrypt the entire bucket while keeping the public read policy","Add request logging to monitor who reads the public objects"], correct:1, explanation:"Separating public assets from private metadata into distinct buckets removes the over-exposure at its root. Encrypting a publicly readable bucket does not help because authorized public reads still decrypt server-side." },
  { id:2033, domain:2, level:3, question:"An organization wants keys for highly regulated data to remain usable only inside its own datacenter even when data lives in the cloud. Which model fits?", options:["Bring-your-own-key importing into the provider HSM","Hold-your-own-key with on-premises HSM performing operations","Provider-managed keys with frequent automatic rotation","Client-side hashing of the data before upload"], correct:1, explanation:"Hold-your-own-key keeps key operations on the customer's on-premises HSM, so keys never become usable in the provider environment. BYOK still places the key inside the provider's HSM for use." },
  { id:2034, domain:3, level:3, question:"A hypervisor escape vulnerability is disclosed for the virtualization platform a CSP uses. From the customer's tenant perspective, what is the MOST appropriate immediate concern?", options:["Whether the application's TLS certificate needs reissuing","Whether the guest OS license remains valid after patching","Whether tenant isolation between VMs could be breached by an attacker","Whether storage costs will rise after the provider patches"], correct:2, explanation:"A hypervisor escape threatens the isolation boundary between co-resident tenant VMs, the core multi-tenant risk. License validity and certificate reissuance are unrelated to the escape's security impact." },
  { id:2035, domain:3, level:3, question:"An architect implements micro-segmentation in a cloud workload. Which outcome is the PRIMARY security benefit over traditional perimeter segmentation?", options:["It constrains east-west lateral movement between workloads","It eliminates the need for any host-based firewall rules","It removes the requirement to encrypt internal traffic","It guarantees compliance with all data residency mandates"], correct:0, explanation:"Micro-segmentation limits east-west lateral movement so a compromised workload cannot freely reach peers. It complements rather than removes host firewalls and does not by itself address residency or encryption." },
  { id:2036, domain:3, level:3, question:"A team runs containers on a shared host. To reduce the blast radius if one container is compromised, which control is MOST effective?", options:["Running all containers as root for operational simplicity","Disabling image scanning to speed up deployment pipelines","Increasing the host's physical memory so it can schedule more containers","Enforcing least-privilege with namespaces, seccomp, and dropped capabilities"], correct:3, explanation:"Least-privilege isolation via namespaces, seccomp, and dropped capabilities limits what a compromised container can do. Running as root expands the blast radius, the opposite of the goal." },
  { id:2037, domain:3, level:3, question:"During datacenter design review for a cloud region, the team evaluates power resilience. Which arrangement BEST supports continuous availability of a Tier III-style facility?", options:["A single utility feed with a manual transfer switch","Redundant power paths with concurrently maintainable components","One large UPS sized for the entire load with no generator","Generators only, with no uninterruptible power supply"], correct:1, explanation:"Redundant, concurrently maintainable power paths allow maintenance without downtime, aligning with high-availability datacenter design. A single feed or single UPS introduces a single point of failure." },
  { id:2038, domain:3, level:3, question:"A cloud network engineer must connect on-premises to the CSP with confidentiality across the public internet at low cost. Which option is the BEST fit?", options:["A dedicated private circuit with no encryption configured","A site-to-site IPsec VPN over the public internet","An unencrypted GRE tunnel between the two networks","Public API calls secured only by API keys"], correct:1, explanation:"A site-to-site IPsec VPN provides encrypted connectivity over the public internet at low cost. A dedicated circuit is costlier and, without encryption, would not meet the confidentiality requirement on its own." },
  { id:2039, domain:3, level:3, question:"An organization plans BCDR for cloud infrastructure and must decide on a recovery strategy that minimizes ongoing cost while meeting a four-hour RTO. Which is MOST appropriate?", options:["Active-active across three regions with full live capacity","Backup-only with restore expected to take roughly a day","Pilot light keeping minimal core services warm for rapid scale-up","Cold site requiring hardware procurement after a disaster"], correct:2, explanation:"Pilot light keeps core services warm so capacity can scale up within hours, balancing cost against a four-hour RTO. Active-active meets the RTO but at far higher ongoing cost than necessary." },
  { id:2040, domain:3, level:3, question:"A virtualization administrator notices VM sprawl is increasing the attack surface. Which governance control MOST directly addresses the root cause?", options:["Enabling at-rest encryption on all of the virtual disk image files","Adding more network IDS sensors across the cluster","Increasing the hypervisor's memory overcommit ratio","Enforcing image lifecycle management with approval and decommission gates"], correct:3, explanation:"Lifecycle management with provisioning approval and decommissioning gates curbs uncontrolled VM creation that drives sprawl. Adding IDS sensors monitors the symptom but does not stop unnecessary VMs from accumulating." },
  { id:2041, domain:3, level:3, question:"A cloud security architect must protect management-plane access to the virtualization infrastructure. Which control is the MOST critical foundation?", options:["Allowing administrators to connect from any corporate workstation","Placing management interfaces on a segregated, restricted network","Sharing one administrative account for faster incident response","Disabling logging on the management plane to reduce noise"], correct:1, explanation:"Segregating and restricting the management network is foundational because management-plane compromise can affect every hosted workload. Shared accounts and disabled logging weaken accountability and detection." },
  { id:2042, domain:3, level:3, question:"A serverless function needs outbound access only to one database. Which network configuration BEST applies least privilege?", options:["Disable the function's network controls and rely on IAM only","Allow the function unrestricted internet egress for flexibility","Place the function in a VPC with egress rules limited to the database","Route all function traffic through a public NAT to any destination"], correct:2, explanation:"Constraining egress to only the database enforces least privilege at the network layer. Unrestricted egress or relying solely on IAM leaves an unnecessary path for exfiltration if the function is compromised." },
  { id:2043, domain:3, level:3, question:"After a tenant reports cross-tenant data exposure in a managed database, the provider investigates. Which infrastructure weakness is the MOST likely root cause to examine FIRST?", options:["A slow autoscaling response during peak traffic","An expired TLS certificate on the management console","Insufficient backup frequency for the affected database","A misconfigured logical isolation boundary in the shared service"], correct:3, explanation:"Cross-tenant exposure points first to a broken logical isolation boundary in the shared service. An expired certificate or backup cadence would not produce cross-tenant data leakage." },
  { id:2044, domain:3, level:3, question:"An engineer must decide how to handle secrets used by infrastructure automation. Which practice MOST reduces the risk of secret leakage in cloud infrastructure code?", options:["Retrieve secrets at runtime from a managed secrets service","Hard-code secrets in the templates for deployment reliability","Store secrets in environment variables committed to the repository","Email the secrets to operators who paste them during deploys"], correct:0, explanation:"Retrieving secrets at runtime from a managed secrets service keeps them out of code and version control. Hard-coding or committing secrets to the repository exposes them to anyone with repo access." },
  { id:2045, domain:3, level:3, question:"A datacenter design must protect against environmental threats in a flood-prone region. Which control decision is the MOST strategic mitigation?", options:["Install additional smoke detectors throughout the facility","Locate critical equipment above projected flood levels with site selection","Increase HVAC capacity to handle higher humidity","Add more biometric readers at each of the main facility entrances and exits"], correct:1, explanation:"Site selection and raising critical equipment above flood levels strategically mitigates the specific environmental threat. Smoke detectors and biometrics address other risks, not flooding." },
  { id:2046, domain:3, level:3, question:"A security team wants to ensure that container images deployed to production are free of known vulnerabilities and unaltered. Which combined control set is BEST?", options:["Network ingress filtering at the cluster edge alone","Manual review of Dockerfiles only before the first release","Runtime CPU limits and memory quotas on each container","Image scanning in the pipeline plus signature verification at deploy"], correct:3, explanation:"Pipeline scanning catches known vulnerabilities while signature verification ensures images were not altered before deployment. Resource limits and ingress filtering address other risks but neither validates image integrity or content." },
  { id:2047, domain:3, level:3, question:"A cloud workload must enforce that traffic between two application tiers is both authenticated and encrypted regardless of network location. Which approach BEST achieves this?", options:["Implement mutual TLS between the services with identity certificates","Rely on the VPC boundary to keep internal traffic private","Open a wide internal security group between the tiers","Use a single shared password validated by each tier"], correct:0, explanation:"Mutual TLS authenticates both endpoints and encrypts traffic independent of network trust, fitting a zero-trust posture. Relying on the VPC boundary assumes the internal network is trustworthy, which it may not be." },
  { id:2048, domain:3, level:3, question:"An architect reviews storage in a cloud HA design and must avoid a single point of failure for a stateful database. Which configuration is MOST appropriate?", options:["A single large volume in one availability zone","Daily snapshots stored in the same zone as the primary","Synchronous replication across zones with automatic failover","Local instance store providing the fastest possible I/O"], correct:2, explanation:"Synchronous cross-zone replication with failover removes the single-zone dependency for a stateful database. A single volume or same-zone snapshots leave a single point of failure if that zone is lost." },
  { id:2049, domain:3, level:3, question:"A penetration test against a cloud network shows that a compromised public web server can reach internal admin ports. What is the BEST corrective control?", options:["Re-image the web server and reset its credentials","Move the web server to a larger instance type","Increase the web server's logging verbosity to capture more detail","Implement segmentation restricting the web tier to required ports only"], correct:3, explanation:"Segmenting the web tier to only required destinations and ports stops the lateral path to admin services. Re-imaging removes the current compromise but leaves the architectural exposure that enabled the reachability." },
  { id:2050, domain:3, level:3, question:"A provider must demonstrate physical security for tenant assurance. Which control MOST directly supports non-repudiation of physical access events?", options:["A sign-in sheet maintained at the reception desk","A guard who visually confirms identities at the door","Locked server cabinets with shared keys among staff","Mantrap entries combined with badge logs and CCTV correlation"], correct:3, explanation:"Mantraps with badge logs and CCTV correlation create strong, time-stamped, attributable records of who entered. A paper sign-in sheet or shared keys lack the integrity needed for non-repudiation." },
  { id:2051, domain:4, level:3, question:"A team performs threat modeling using STRIDE on a new API. They identify that an attacker could replay captured requests. Which STRIDE category does this MOST directly map to, and what control is BEST?", options:["Tampering, addressed by input validation on all parameters","Repudiation, addressed by verbose application logging","Spoofing/Replay, addressed by nonces and short-lived tokens","Denial of service, addressed by rate limiting at the gateway"], correct:2, explanation:"Replay attacks fall under spoofing/authentication concerns and are best countered with nonces and short-lived tokens. Input validation addresses tampering, a different threat, and would not prevent valid-but-replayed requests." },
  { id:2052, domain:4, level:3, question:"During secure SDLC, the team must catch vulnerabilities in source before runtime while developers code. Which testing type is the MOST appropriate to integrate FIRST?", options:["Static application security testing on the source code","Dynamic application security testing against a running build","Interactive testing requiring full production deployment","Manual penetration testing scheduled quarterly"], correct:0, explanation:"SAST analyzes source code early, giving developers feedback before runtime. DAST requires a running application and therefore comes later in the lifecycle than the FIRST source-level check." },
  { id:2053, domain:4, level:3, question:"A microservices application uses many open-source libraries. Management worries about vulnerable transitive dependencies. Which practice MOST directly addresses this concern?", options:["Increasing unit test coverage of business logic","Adding a web application firewall in front of the services","Encrypting all inter-service traffic with mutual TLS","Software composition analysis tracking dependency vulnerabilities"], correct:3, explanation:"Software composition analysis inventories dependencies, including transitive ones, and flags known vulnerabilities. A WAF and mutual TLS protect runtime traffic but do not identify vulnerable library components." },
  { id:2054, domain:4, level:3, question:"An architect designs federation so a SaaS app trusts the enterprise IdP. Which protocol element is MOST critical to validate to prevent token forgery?", options:["The signature on the assertion using the IdP's trusted key","The display name shown to the user after login","The color scheme of the SaaS login page","The order in which attributes appear in the token"], correct:0, explanation:"Validating the assertion's signature against the IdP's trusted key prevents forged tokens from being accepted. Display attributes and styling have no bearing on the token's authenticity." },
  { id:2055, domain:4, level:3, question:"A serverless function exposes a public endpoint. The team wants to enforce authentication and throttling consistently. Which component is BEST suited to centralize these controls?", options:["A second copy of the function for redundancy","A larger memory allocation on the function","An API gateway in front of the function","A client-side JavaScript check in the browser"], correct:2, explanation:"An API gateway centralizes authentication, authorization, and throttling for serverless endpoints. Client-side checks are trivially bypassed and provide no real enforcement." },
  { id:2056, domain:4, level:3, question:"A developer stores a database password in the application's container image to simplify deployment. Why is this a significant security weakness?", options:["It increases the container image size unnecessarily","It causes the image to fail vulnerability scanning automatically","It prevents the container from starting without network access","Anyone who pulls the image can extract the embedded secret"], correct:3, explanation:"Embedding secrets in an image means anyone with image access can extract them, a serious exposure. The core issue is secret leakage, not image size or startup behavior." },
  { id:2057, domain:4, level:3, question:"A CASB is being deployed to govern sanctioned and unsanctioned SaaS use. Which CASB capability MOST directly addresses shadow IT discovery?", options:["Inline data loss prevention on sanctioned app traffic","Single sign-on enforcement for the corporate email suite","Analysis of network and proxy logs to identify cloud app usage","Encryption of files before they upload to sanctioned storage"], correct:2, explanation:"Analyzing logs to surface which cloud apps employees use is how a CASB discovers shadow IT. Inline DLP and SSO govern known/sanctioned apps but do not reveal unsanctioned ones." },
  { id:2058, domain:4, level:3, question:"During design, the team debates DREAD scoring for two findings. Finding A is trivially exploitable and affects all users; Finding B requires insider access and affects one record. Which should be prioritized and why?", options:["Finding A, due to higher exploitability and broader impact","Finding B, because insider threats are always most severe","Both equally, since DREAD weights all factors identically","Neither, since DREAD only applies to network attacks"], correct:0, explanation:"DREAD prioritizes by combined risk; Finding A scores higher on exploitability and affected users, so it comes first. Assuming insider threats are always most severe ignores DREAD's actual scoring of impact and exploitability." },
  { id:2059, domain:4, level:3, question:"A CI/CD pipeline pulls build tools from public registries. To reduce supply-chain risk, which control is the MOST effective?", options:["Running the pipeline more frequently to catch issues sooner","Pinning and verifying dependency versions from a curated internal registry","Allowing the pipeline broad internet access for convenience","Disabling pipeline logging entirely to speed up the build process"], correct:1, explanation:"Pinning verified versions sourced from a curated registry reduces the risk of malicious or altered components entering builds. Running builds more often does not address the integrity of pulled components." },
  { id:2060, domain:4, level:3, question:"An application requires strong identity assurance for high-value transactions. Single-factor passwords are deemed insufficient. Which control BEST raises assurance without crippling usability?", options:["Forcing password changes every fifteen days for all users","Storing passwords with a faster, cheaper hashing algorithm","Lengthening the minimum password to thirty characters","Adding phishing-resistant MFA for high-value transaction flows"], correct:3, explanation:"Phishing-resistant MFA on high-value flows raises assurance where it matters while keeping routine usability acceptable. Frequent forced password changes harm usability and provide weak security benefit." },
  { id:2061, domain:4, level:3, question:"A reviewer finds that an API returns detailed stack traces on errors. From a secure design view, what is the BEST remediation?", options:["Return generic error messages and log details server-side","Disable the API entirely until a redesign is complete","Encrypt the stack traces before returning them to clients","Increase the API's timeout to reduce error frequency"], correct:0, explanation:"Returning generic errors to clients while logging details server-side prevents information disclosure without losing diagnostics. Encrypting traces sent to clients still leaks data to whoever can decrypt at the endpoint." },
  { id:2062, domain:4, level:3, question:"In software assurance, the team must validate that a third-party component behaves as claimed before integration. Which activity is MOST appropriate?", options:["Trusting the vendor's marketing datasheet as sufficient evidence","Independent testing and review of the component against requirements","Deploying it directly to production to observe real behavior","Renaming the component to match internal naming standards"], correct:1, explanation:"Independent testing and review validate the component against stated requirements before trusting it. Relying on vendor marketing provides no objective assurance, and production deployment to observe behavior is reckless." },
  { id:2063, domain:4, level:3, question:"A team adopts IAST to improve testing. Which characteristic of IAST MOST justifies adding it alongside existing SAST and DAST?", options:["It analyzes code at rest without executing the application","It entirely replaces the need for any third-party dependency analysis","It observes the running app from inside to find real exploitable flaws","It only scans network packets between microservices"], correct:2, explanation:"IAST instruments the running application to correlate runtime behavior with code, reducing false positives that pure SAST or DAST produce. It does not analyze code at rest, which is SAST's role." },
  { id:2064, domain:4, level:3, question:"A microservice authorizes requests by trusting a header set by an upstream service. A reviewer flags this. What is the BEST fix?", options:["Validate a cryptographically signed token at each service","Document the trust assumption in the architecture diagram","Rename the header to something harder to guess","Restrict the header to lowercase characters only"], correct:0, explanation:"Validating a signed token at each service prevents header spoofing if an attacker reaches the internal network. Documenting or obscuring the header does nothing to stop a forged header from being trusted." },
  { id:2065, domain:4, level:3, question:"During SDLC, security requirements were not defined up front and are being retrofitted near release. What is the PRIMARY risk this introduces?", options:["An increased need for additional inline source code comments","Slightly larger documentation for the project archive","Reduced developer familiarity with the chosen language","Costlier, less effective fixes due to late discovery of design flaws"], correct:3, explanation:"Retrofitting security late means design flaws surface when they are most expensive and disruptive to fix. The risk is cost and effectiveness of remediation, not documentation volume." },
  { id:2066, domain:4, level:3, question:"An organization wants developers to receive secrets without ever seeing them in plaintext in code or config. Which pattern BEST achieves this?", options:["Sharing secrets in a team chat channel with restricted membership","Encrypting the config file and committing it to the repository","Injecting secrets at runtime from a vault via short-lived leases","Storing secrets base64-encoded in environment files"], correct:2, explanation:"Runtime injection from a vault with short-lived leases keeps secrets out of code and limits exposure window. Base64 encoding is not encryption, and committed encrypted files still risk key and ciphertext exposure together." },
  { id:2067, domain:5, level:3, question:"A SOC analyst sees a spike in failed logins followed by a single success from a new geography for a privileged account. What is the BEST FIRST response action?", options:["Disable the account session and require re-authentication with MFA","Wait to see whether further suspicious activity occurs","Delete the account immediately to stop the attacker","Increase log retention settings for the affected system only"], correct:0, explanation:"Disabling the session and forcing MFA re-authentication contains a likely credential-stuffing success without destroying evidence. Deleting the account is destructive and hampers investigation, while waiting allows the attacker to act." },
  { id:2068, domain:5, level:3, question:"An operations team must apply a critical patch to a fleet while minimizing risk of widespread outage. Which deployment approach is MOST appropriate?", options:["Stage the patch through canary and phased rings with monitoring","Patch all systems simultaneously to close the window fastest","Delay patching until the next quarterly maintenance window","Patch only the systems that have reported errors recently"], correct:0, explanation:"Canary and phased rings limit blast radius and allow rollback if the patch causes issues, balancing speed and stability. Patching everything at once risks a fleet-wide outage from a bad patch." },
  { id:2069, domain:5, level:3, question:"During incident response, an analyst wants to preserve volatile evidence from a compromised cloud VM before remediation. Which action should occur FIRST?", options:["Reboot the affected VM to try to clear the attacker's foothold","Restore the VM from last night's backup immediately","Capture a memory snapshot and disk image of the running instance","Reinstall the operating system from a clean image"], correct:2, explanation:"Capturing memory and disk images first preserves volatile evidence for forensic analysis. Rebooting or restoring destroys volatile state and undermines the investigation." },
  { id:2070, domain:5, level:3, question:"A change to a production network ACL caused an outage. The change followed no formal review. Which process improvement MOST directly prevents recurrence?", options:["Enforce change management with peer review and rollback plans","Increase the monitoring dashboard refresh rate for visibility","Add more staff to the on-call rotation schedule","Purchase a larger network appliance for capacity"], correct:0, explanation:"Formal change management with peer review and rollback plans addresses the root cause: an unreviewed change. More monitoring or staff does not prevent an unvetted change from being applied." },
  { id:2071, domain:5, level:3, question:"A SIEM generates many low-fidelity alerts, causing analyst fatigue. Which improvement BEST raises detection effectiveness?", options:["Forward every raw log to analysts for manual review","Reduce log sources to lower the alert volume","Disable alerting during business hours to reduce noise","Tune correlation rules and enrich alerts with threat context"], correct:3, explanation:"Tuning correlation rules and enriching with context raises alert fidelity so analysts focus on real threats. Disabling alerts or cutting log sources reduces noise by also reducing legitimate detection coverage." },
  { id:2072, domain:5, level:3, question:"During the build phase of a logical environment, the team must ensure baseline security across many instances. Which approach is MOST effective and repeatable?", options:["Deploying from hardened, version-controlled golden images","Manually hardening each instance after it boots","Allowing each team to configure instances as they prefer","Hardening only the instances that fail an audit later"], correct:0, explanation:"Hardened golden images under version control deliver consistent, repeatable baselines at scale. Manual per-instance hardening is error-prone and drifts, undermining consistency." },
  { id:2073, domain:5, level:3, question:"An organization must communicate a confirmed data breach to stakeholders. Which principle should MOST guide the operations team's external communication?", options:["Follow the predefined plan, coordinating with legal and approved spokespeople","Release maximum technical detail immediately to appear transparent","Let individual engineers answer customer questions directly","Withhold all information indefinitely to avoid liability"], correct:0, explanation:"Coordinated communication through the predefined plan, legal, and approved spokespeople ensures accuracy and regulatory alignment. Ad hoc engineer responses or premature technical detail can create legal exposure and misinformation." },
  { id:2074, domain:5, level:3, question:"A vulnerability scan reports a critical finding on an internet-facing service, but exploitation requires a credential the attacker is unlikely to have. What is the BEST prioritization decision?", options:["Treat raw severity as final and patch within the hour","Ignore the finding because a credential is required","Assess exploitability and exposure to set a risk-based priority","Escalate to executives before any technical assessment"], correct:2, explanation:"Combining severity with real exploitability and exposure yields a defensible risk-based priority. Treating the raw score as final ignores mitigating context, while ignoring it dismisses real residual risk." },
  { id:2075, domain:5, level:3, question:"An operations team adopts ITIL practices. They want to reduce repeat incidents caused by the same underlying fault. Which ITIL process is MOST relevant?", options:["Capacity management to forecast resource demand","Incident management to restore service as fast as possible","Problem management to identify and remove root causes","Release management to schedule software deployments"], correct:2, explanation:"Problem management addresses recurring incidents by finding and eliminating root causes. Incident management focuses on restoring service, not preventing recurrence." },
  { id:2076, domain:5, level:3, question:"Logs from cloud workloads are stored only locally on each instance. After an instance is terminated during an attack, the logs are lost. What is the BEST design correction?", options:["Increase the local disk size on each instance","Compress local logs to retain more history on the instance","Take weekly backups of each instance's local logs","Centralize log collection to durable, separate storage in real time"], correct:3, explanation:"Real-time centralized logging to durable separate storage survives instance termination and supports investigation. Larger local disks or weekly backups still lose logs when the instance is destroyed mid-attack." },
  { id:2077, domain:5, level:3, question:"A forensic investigator must collect evidence from a CSP-managed PaaS where the customer lacks OS access. What is the MOST realistic approach?", options:["Image the underlying physical server directly","Request provider-supported logs and artifacts via the agreed process","Install a kernel agent on the managed platform","Demand raw hypervisor memory from the provider on the spot"], correct:1, explanation:"In managed PaaS the customer must rely on provider-supported logs and artifacts obtained through agreed processes. Direct imaging or kernel agents are not possible because the customer lacks that level of access." },
  { id:2078, domain:5, level:3, question:"A configuration management audit finds drift between deployed infrastructure and the declared baseline. Which practice MOST directly prevents future drift?", options:["Manually reconciling configurations during quarterly reviews","Granting more administrators direct console access","Enforcing infrastructure as code with automated drift detection","Documenting the intended configuration in a wiki"], correct:2, explanation:"Infrastructure as code with automated drift detection continuously enforces the declared baseline. Quarterly manual reconciliation and wiki documentation do not prevent drift between reviews." },
  { id:2079, domain:5, level:3, question:"During an incident, the team must decide between immediate eradication and continued monitoring to understand attacker scope. Which factor MOST justifies short-term continued monitoring?", options:["The desire to avoid filling out incident paperwork","A preference to schedule eradication during business hours","Need to scope the full compromise before the attacker is tipped off","The goal of generating more SIEM alerts for metrics"], correct:2, explanation:"Continued monitoring can be justified to scope the full compromise so eradication is complete and the attacker is not prematurely alerted. Convenience or metrics are not legitimate justifications for delaying containment." },
  { id:2080, domain:5, level:3, question:"A team runs a SOC and wants to measure detection quality over time. Which metric is the MOST meaningful indicator of detection effectiveness?", options:["Total number of raw events ingested per day","Total storage consumed by the log archive","Number of dashboards built by analysts","Mean time to detect genuine incidents"], correct:3, explanation:"Mean time to detect genuine incidents directly reflects how quickly real threats are identified. Raw event volume and storage are activity measures, not indicators of detection effectiveness." },
  { id:2081, domain:5, level:3, question:"An operations engineer must roll out an emergency patch outside the normal cycle. Which control BEST preserves governance while allowing speed?", options:["Skip all approvals since it is an emergency","Use the documented emergency change process with after-the-fact review","Wait for the next scheduled change window regardless of urgency","Let the engineer decide unilaterally without any record"], correct:1, explanation:"A documented emergency change process allows rapid action while preserving accountability through after-the-fact review. Skipping approvals entirely or acting without records destroys governance and traceability." },
  { id:2082, domain:5, level:3, question:"A monitoring strategy must detect both known signatures and novel anomalous behavior in cloud workloads. Which combination is the BEST?", options:["Signature-based detection only, for low false positives","Relying solely on the CSP's default alerting","Manual log review by analysts once per week","Signature-based plus behavioral anomaly detection"], correct:3, explanation:"Combining signature-based and behavioral anomaly detection catches both known and novel threats. Signature-only detection misses novel attacks, and weekly manual review is far too slow for cloud-scale activity." },
  { id:2083, domain:5, level:3, question:"After patching a critical CVE, the operations team must confirm the fix was effective fleet-wide. Which verification step is MOST appropriate?", options:["Assume success because the patch command returned no errors","Re-scan the fleet and validate the vulnerability is no longer present","Ask each team to self-attest that they patched","Wait for users to report whether anything broke"], correct:1, explanation:"Re-scanning and validating absence of the vulnerability provides objective confirmation across the fleet. A successful command return or self-attestation does not prove the underlying flaw is closed." },
  { id:2084, domain:6, level:3, question:"A company operating in the EU processes personal data and is deciding the lawful basis under GDPR for a new analytics feature. Which approach is MOST defensible when the processing is not strictly necessary for the service?", options:["Obtain freely given, specific, informed consent for the analytics","Rely on legitimate interest without any balancing assessment","Assume contractual necessity covers all secondary processing","Process first and seek consent only if a regulator inquires"], correct:0, explanation:"For non-essential processing, freely given, specific, informed consent is the most defensible GDPR basis. Claiming legitimate interest without a balancing test or stretching contractual necessity is legally weak." },
  { id:2085, domain:6, level:3, question:"An organization receives an eDiscovery request for data spread across multiple cloud regions in different countries. Which concern should be addressed FIRST?", options:["Compressing the data primarily to reduce network transfer costs","Renaming files to match the case reference number","Choosing the fastest storage tier for retrieval","Conflicting legal jurisdictions and cross-border data transfer rules"], correct:3, explanation:"Cross-border eDiscovery first raises jurisdictional conflicts and transfer-law constraints that can prohibit or restrict production. Cost and file naming are secondary to lawful collection across jurisdictions." },
  { id:2086, domain:6, level:3, question:"During vendor due diligence, a CSP provides a SOC 2 Type II report. What does this report MOST meaningfully demonstrate to the customer?", options:["A point-in-time design assessment of the controls only","Operating effectiveness of controls over a defined period","Certification that the provider meets every regulation globally","A guarantee that no breach can ever occur at the provider"], correct:1, explanation:"A SOC 2 Type II evaluates the operating effectiveness of controls over a period, not just their design at a point in time. It is neither a universal compliance certification nor a breach guarantee." },
  { id:2087, domain:6, level:3, question:"A risk assessment identifies a high-impact, low-likelihood threat to a cloud workload that would be very costly to fully mitigate. Which response is MOST appropriate to evaluate FIRST?", options:["Accept the risk without documenting any rationale","Ignore the risk because likelihood is low","Transfer or share the risk, for example via cyber insurance","Mitigate it fully regardless of cost-effectiveness"], correct:2, explanation:"For high-impact, low-likelihood, costly-to-mitigate risks, transferring or sharing the risk is a sound option to evaluate. Accepting without rationale or ignoring it abandons due diligence, and full mitigation may not be cost-justified." },
  { id:2088, domain:6, level:3, question:"A contract negotiation with a CSP centers on the SLA. Which clause is MOST important from a security-and-compliance standpoint, beyond uptime guarantees?", options:["The color of the provider's status dashboard","The number of regions the provider advertises","The marketing name of the support tier","Breach notification timelines and the right to audit"], correct:3, explanation:"Breach notification timelines and audit rights are essential security and compliance provisions in an SLA. Dashboard styling and marketing tier names carry no compliance weight." },
  { id:2089, domain:6, level:3, question:"An auditor performs a gap analysis against ISO/IEC 27001 for a cloud deployment. What is the PRIMARY purpose of this exercise?", options:["To assign blame for past security incidents","To compare current controls against the standard's requirements","To replace the organization's risk assessment process entirely","To certify the cloud provider on the customer's behalf"], correct:1, explanation:"A gap analysis identifies where current controls fall short of the standard's requirements so they can be remediated. It is not about assigning blame or certifying the provider." },
  { id:2090, domain:6, level:3, question:"A multinational stores customer data in a CSP and must comply with conflicting national laws on government data access. Which strategy MOST directly reduces legal exposure?", options:["Publicly state the company disagrees with the conflicting laws","Encrypt data with customer-held keys and localize per jurisdiction","Move all data to a single region to simplify operations","Delete all data older than thirty days automatically"], correct:1, explanation:"Customer-held keys plus jurisdictional localization limit unauthorized access and align storage with applicable law. Consolidating into one region or blanket deletion does not resolve the conflicting access obligations." },
  { id:2091, domain:6, level:3, question:"A supply-chain risk review finds a critical subprocessor that the primary CSP did not disclose. Which contractual control would have MOST directly prevented this gap?", options:["A clause specifying the font in the contract","A clause setting the monthly invoice due date","A clause defining the provider's brand usage rights","A clause requiring disclosure and approval of subprocessors"], correct:3, explanation:"A subprocessor disclosure-and-approval clause ensures the customer knows and consents to who handles their data downstream. Billing and branding clauses have no bearing on supply-chain transparency." },
  { id:2092, domain:6, level:3, question:"A privacy officer must decide whether a planned cross-border transfer of EU personal data to a third country is lawful. Which mechanism is the MOST appropriate to rely on when no adequacy decision exists?", options:["Proceed because the data is encrypted in transit","Use standard contractual clauses with a transfer impact assessment","Anonymize the data after it has already been transferred","Assume the recipient country is adequate by default"], correct:1, explanation:"Without an adequacy decision, standard contractual clauses paired with a transfer impact assessment provide a lawful transfer mechanism. Encryption in transit alone does not satisfy GDPR transfer requirements, nor can adequacy be assumed." },
  { id:2093, domain:6, level:3, question:"During an audit, the provider declines to share its full internal penetration test results, offering a SOC 2 report and a bridge letter instead. What is the BEST interpretation for the customer?", options:["The provider is hiding a breach and should be terminated","The customer can legally compel the raw report at any time","Reliance on independent attestations is normal when raw reports are restricted","The SOC 2 report is worthless without also obtaining the raw test data"], correct:2, explanation:"Relying on independent attestations like SOC 2 and bridge letters is standard practice when providers restrict raw test data for confidentiality. Assuming a hidden breach or dismissing the SOC 2 report overreaches the available evidence." },
  { id:2094, domain:6, level:3, question:"A company must select a risk framework to structure its cloud risk program consistently. Which selection rationale is MOST sound?", options:["Choose whichever framework has the shortest documentation","Choose a recognized framework aligned to regulatory and business context","Choose the framework a competitor mentioned once publicly","Choose to invent a proprietary framework with no external basis"], correct:1, explanation:"Selecting a recognized framework aligned to the organization's regulatory and business context ensures relevance and credibility. Choosing by document length or copying a competitor's offhand mention lacks sound basis." },
  { id:2095, domain:6, level:3, question:"A data processing agreement must address what happens to data when the contract ends. Which provision is MOST important to include?", options:["A clause describing the provider's office holiday schedule","A clause naming the provider's preferred conference venue","A clause requiring secure return or verified deletion of data","A clause about the provider's social media handles"], correct:2, explanation:"End-of-contract secure return or verified deletion of data is critical to prevent residual exposure after termination. Holiday schedules and social media handles are irrelevant to data protection." },
  { id:2096, domain:6, level:3, question:"An organization conducts a privacy impact assessment for a new cloud service handling sensitive data. What is the PRIMARY output that should drive subsequent decisions?", options:["A marketing summary of the service's new features","A list of competitors offering similar services","Identified privacy risks with recommended mitigations","An estimate of expected advertising revenue"], correct:2, explanation:"A PIA's primary output is identified privacy risks with recommended mitigations to inform design and deployment decisions. Marketing summaries and revenue estimates are not the assessment's purpose." },
  { id:2097, domain:6, level:3, question:"A regulator requires demonstrable accountability for how personal data flows through a cloud system. Which artifact MOST directly satisfies this?", options:["A high-level network diagram with no data details","A documented record of processing activities and data flows","A copy of the company's quarterly financial statement","A screenshot of the cloud console login page"], correct:1, explanation:"A documented record of processing activities and data flows directly demonstrates accountability for personal data handling. A generic network diagram or financial statement does not show how personal data is processed." },
  { id:2098, domain:6, level:3, question:"A customer wants assurance that a CSP's controls relevant to financial reporting are sound. Which report type is MOST appropriate to request?", options:["SOC 2 focused on security and availability principles","SOC 1 focused on controls relevant to financial reporting","SOC 3 general-use seal for public marketing","A penetration test executive summary only"], correct:1, explanation:"SOC 1 specifically addresses controls relevant to a customer's financial reporting. SOC 2 covers trust services like security and availability, not financial reporting assertions." },
  { id:2099, domain:6, level:3, question:"During vendor risk management, an organization must decide how often to reassess a critical cloud provider. Which approach is the MOST risk-aligned?", options:["Reassess only once at onboarding and never again","Reassess only if the provider raises its prices","Reassess periodically and upon significant changes or incidents","Reassess at random intervals without any clearly defined trigger"], correct:2, explanation:"Periodic reassessment plus triggers for significant changes or incidents keeps vendor risk current and proportionate. A one-time onboarding assessment leaves risk unmonitored as the relationship and threats evolve." },
  { id:2100, domain:6, level:3, question:"A company faces a legal hold on data residing in a CSP that has automated lifecycle deletion enabled. What is the MOST important immediate action?", options:["Allow lifecycle deletion to continue to save storage costs","Suspend automated deletion to preserve data under the hold","Move the data to a cheaper archival tier without changes","Notify only the finance team about the storage impact"], correct:1, explanation:"Suspending automated deletion is essential to comply with a legal hold and avoid spoliation. Allowing lifecycle deletion to continue would destroy data that must be preserved, exposing the company to sanctions." }
];
